    correctAnswer: 'A',
    explanation: 'Choice A is correct. Stereotype threat (Steele & Aronson) refers to the situational predicament in which individuals are aware of being at risk of confirming a negative stereotype about their social group. When the test was framed as an intelligence measure, this activated the stereotype threat — students expended cognitive resources managing the threat (monitoring, anxiety, self-doubt), which interfered with performance. Crucially, the same students performed equivalently when the threat was removed (non-diagnostic framing). The effect is situational, not dispositional.',
