    question: 'During a clinical presentation, a medical student gives a confident but incorrect diagnosis. The supervising attending thinks: "This student lacks basic pathophysiological understanding," rather than considering that the student may be anxious in a high-stakes setting. The student, if asked later, would likely attribute her error to the pressure of the presentation. Which pair of concepts best describes these two attributions?',
    choices: [
      { label: 'A', text: 'Fundamental attribution error (attending\'s attribution); actor-observer bias (student\'s attribution)' },
      { label: 'B', text: 'Self-serving bias (attending\'s attribution); fundamental attribution error (student\'s attribution)' },
      { label: 'C', text: 'In-group bias (attending\'s attribution); out-group homogeneity (student\'s attribution)' },
      { label: 'D', text: 'Availability heuristic (attending\'s attribution); representativeness heuristic (student\'s attribution)' },
    ],
    correctAnswer: 'A',
    explanation: 'Choice A is correct. Fundamental attribution error (FAE): the attending (as observer) overattributes the student\'s incorrect diagnosis to a stable dispositional trait ("lacks understanding") while underweighting situational factors (high-stakes anxiety). This is the classic FAE — observers overemphasize internal/dispositional causes. Actor-observer bias: the student (as actor) attributes her own behavior to the situation ("pressure of the presentation") — actors tend to see situational factors as explaining their own behavior. These two biases are related: FAE occurs when an observer applies the dispositional bias; actor-observer bias describes how actors and observers systematically differ in their attributions for the same behavior.',
    wrongAnswerExplanations: {
      B: 'Self-serving bias involves attributing successes to internal factors and failures to external factors, specifically to protect self-esteem. The attending is not attributing the student\'s failure to protect the attending\'s own self-esteem — the attending is evaluating someone else. Self-serving bias applies to self-evaluation, not to judgment of others.',
      C: 'In-group bias is favoritism toward one\'s own group. Out-group homogeneity is perceiving out-group members as more similar to each other than in-group members. The scenario is about attribution style in an individual dyadic interaction, not about group membership effects. No group dynamics are involved.',
      D: 'The availability heuristic is using how easily an example comes to mind to estimate frequency or probability. Representativeness heuristic is judging probability based on similarity to a prototype. These are cognitive shortcuts for probability estimation, not processes governing attribution of behavior to causes.',
    },
    teachingPoint: 'Attribution biases: FAE (observer) — overemphasize disposition, underemphasize situation. Actor-observer bias — actors attribute behavior to situation; observers attribute to disposition (FAE is the observer side of this). Self-serving bias — self-serving attribution: claim credit for success (internal), blame failure on external. These three biases appear frequently on the MCAT. Distinguish: FAE is about observer → other; self-serving is about self → own behavior.',
    relatedTopics: ['Fundamental attribution error', 'Actor-observer bias', 'Attribution theory', 'Dispositional vs situational attribution', 'Social cognition'],
