    correctAnswer: 'B',
    explanation: 'Choice B is correct. Absolute poverty is defined by a fixed, context-independent threshold of income or material deprivation below which basic needs (food, shelter, clothing) cannot be met — this threshold does not change with social context. Relative poverty is defined relative to the median or average income in a given society — a household is "poor" if its income is substantially below the social median, even if basic survival needs are technically met. Relative poverty captures social exclusion and inequality rather than absolute deprivation.',
