    question: 'A rat is trained to press a lever for food under two schedules: Schedule 1 rewards every 15th press (fixed-ratio, FR-15); Schedule 2 rewards on average every 15 presses in an unpredictable, variable pattern (variable-ratio, VR-15). Extinction is then imposed with no rewards given. Which prediction is MOST consistent with established learning theory?',
    choices: [
      { label: 'A', text: 'FR-15 produces slower extinction because fixed schedules create stronger conditioning than variable schedules' },
      { label: 'B', text: 'VR-15 produces slower extinction because the unpredictable reinforcement schedule makes it harder to discriminate extinction from the variable reinforcement contingency, maintaining higher responding for longer' },
      { label: 'C', text: 'Both schedules produce identical extinction rates because the average reinforcement rate (1 per 15 presses) is equal' },
      { label: 'D', text: 'FR-15 produces slower extinction because the post-reinforcement pause trains the rat to persist through unrewarded periods' },
    ],
    correctAnswer: 'B',
    explanation: 'Choice B is correct. Variable-ratio schedules produce the greatest resistance to extinction — a fundamental finding of operant conditioning research (Skinner). The mechanism: on a VR schedule, the animal cannot distinguish "extinction has begun" from "this is just a long unrewarded run before the next reward." On an FR schedule, the predictable pattern (every 15th press) makes non-reward after the 15th press a clear signal that extinction has begun, producing faster discrimination and faster response decline. Additionally, VR schedules produce the highest and most consistent response rates (no post-reinforcement pause) during acquisition.',
    wrongAnswerExplanations: {
      A: 'FR schedules produce higher rates during acquisition due to clear contingency, but they produce FASTER extinction (not slower) because the violation of the fixed pattern signals the onset of extinction immediately. The consistent pattern becomes a discriminative cue whose absence signals extinction.',
      C: 'Equal average reinforcement rates do not produce equal extinction rates. The temporal pattern (predictable vs. variable) matters critically. Identical average rates with different schedules produce substantially different extinction rates — this is a fundamental demonstration that schedule structure, not just rate, determines behavior.',
      D: 'The post-reinforcement pause is a feature of FR schedules where the animal slows responding immediately after each reinforcement. This represents a brief period of non-responding, not a training to "persist through unrewarded periods." The pause, if anything, trains discrimination of post-reinforcement non-reward from the pre-reinforcement non-reward, speeding extinction.',
    },
    teachingPoint: 'Reinforcement schedules and extinction resistance (from most to least resistant): VR > FR > VI > FI. VR is most resistant to extinction because the unpredictable pattern makes extinction indistinguishable from a long inter-reinforcement interval. FR has the post-reinforcement pause and produces faster extinction. Clinical applications: gambling (slot machines = VR → extremely hard to extinguish); intermittent praise (VR) is more motivating and durable than consistent praise (FR).',
